{
  "texts": [
    "Here, the vectors e 13, e 14 and e 24 prescribe the conservation over time t ≥ 0 of the partial densities c 1,∞ + c 3,∞, c 1,∞ + c 4,∞ and c 2,∞ + c 4,∞ within the chemical reactions (this property is clearly visible from relations (17)), where c i,∞ denotes the concentration of the species S i.",
    "Similarly, the collision invariants v 1 m, v 2 m and v 3 m give the conservation of total momentum inside the reactive mixture, while 1 2 |v| 2 m + E ensures the conservation of total (kinetic and chemical, or internal) energy.",
    "In particular, the Boltzmann equation ( 6), the invariance of mass m 1 + m 2 = m 3 + m 4 in the reaction (9) and relations (18) imply that the quantities (19) c ∞ = 4 i=1 R 3 ×T 3 F i (t, x, v)dvdx, ρ ∞ u ∞ = 4 i=1 R 3 ×T 3 m i vF i (t, x, v)dvdx 3 2 K B ρ ∞ T ∞ = 4 i=1 R 3 ×T 3 1 2 m i |v -u ∞ | 2 + E i F i (t, x, v)dvdx,are preserved for any time t ≥ 0.",
    "Here, c ∞ = 4 i=1 c i,∞ stands for the total concentration of the mixture, while ρ ∞ = 4 i=1 m i c i,∞ defines the total density of the mixture, ρ ∞ u ∞ its total momentum and 3 2 K B ρ ∞ T ∞ its total energy.With these global quantities preserved by the kinetic equation, one can deduce an H-theorem [29, Proposition 1] for the combination of the operators Q EL and Q CH.",
    "While the inert component pushes the solution of the Boltzmann equation to relax toward a collisional equilibrium having the shape of a local Maxwellian, the chemical component imposes a further condition binding together the corresponding local concentrations, local temperature, molecular masses and impinging energy of the reaction."
  ]
